<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-249-754  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 249 754.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  March 1990 v9 n3 p63(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiberoptics for practical sensing applications (II): theboundaries of the fiber-sensing universe expand vigorously.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wohlstein, Scott D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiberoptic sensing techniques have a number of practicalapplications because fiber has several advantages over othermethods.andP;  Fiber's advantages include immunity to electromagneticand radio-frequency interference, its potential for high datarates, and its electrical passivity in explosive environments,making it ideal for hostile environments.andP;  Fiberoptics have greatpotential in the medical field where they can be used formonitoring temperature and pressure of critical organs, analysisof blood constituents in vivo, and the delivery and analysis oflight emission therapy at specific remote areas of the body.andO;Fiberoptic sensors also have potential in many other areas,including temperature, pressure and stress measurement on variouskinds of vehicles, instruments and machines in the commercialarena.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsSensorsResearch and DevelopmentApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Complete system layout for a fiberoptic temperature transducersystem. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>